class Solution {
public:
    char repeatedCharacter(string s) {
        unordered_set<char> seen;
        for (char c : s) {
            if (seen.find(c) != seen.end()) {
                return c;
            }
            seen.insert(c);
        }
        return '\0'; // This line will never be reached due to the problem constraints
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution iterates through the string once, using an unordered_set to keep track of characters it has seen. It returns the first character that is found to be already in the set, fulfilling the condition of being the first letter to appear twice. The use of an unordered_set allows for constant time complexity for the insert and find operations, making the overall time complexity linear with respect to the string length. The space complexity is considered O(1) because the maximum size of the set is limited by the number of unique lowercase English letters, which is 26.

